{{Infobox person |name = Margaret Tor-Thompson |alma_mater = World Harvest Theological Seminary |birth_name = |birth_date =9 September 1962 |birth_place = |death_date = {{death date and age|2007|4|4|1962|9|9}} |death_place = [[Monrovia, Liberia]] |known_for = FAPL presidential candidate in the [[Liberian general election, 2005|October 2005 elections]] |citizenship = Liberia}}
Dr. Rev. '''Margaret Tor-Thompson''' (9 September 1962 – 4 April 2007) was a [[Liberia]]n politician and member of the [[Freedom Alliance Party of Liberia]] (FAPL). She has completed her doctorate in Biblical Studies.<ref>{{cite report|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:agnubN5ki6EJ:www.gvsu.edu/cms3/assets/0B4E40FA-03CD-1029-5219639A55372427/UmojaAll%252011%252026%252006.pdf+Margaret+Thompson+Liberia&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESgK9QJnITwSO2iAuoSOyWauwB56RtlFcUcm7oj5I26hzuAg4U8dXR9QSWgNMmtQGW_al2NdsRfncPtf4-X31-gokEzMJwGd5ey2nPKHc2jGiv97gd1yXgOyLEdnqXflm1bH3EGk&sig=AHIEtbQln8L9h0NfwKkyxQbE2VIQZfDjoA |title=Elections and Voting Behavior: The Case of the 2005 Liberian Elections|publisher=GVSU.edu|accessdate=7 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Margaret Tor-Thompson profile|url=http://www.guide2womenleaders.com/candidates2000.htm|publisher=Guide 2 Women Leaders|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>
Tor-Thompson had her early education in Saint Mary's Elementary & Junior High School, William R. Tolbert High School, St. Theresa's Convent and the American Cooperative School. She graduated in nursing in the [[United States of America]], from nursing at [[Loma Linda University]] and received her doctorate from the World Harvest Theological Seminary on Bible studies.
She was the FAPL presidential candidate in the [[Liberian general election, 2005|October 2005 elections]] and was placed 13th out of 22 candidates, receiving only 0.9% of the vote. She was one of three female presidential candidates in the election, with oen of them, [[Ellen Johnson Sirleaf]] went on to winning the election. She died of [[breast cancer]] at [[Bushrod Island]] on 4 April 2007.
==Early life== Tor-Thompson had her early education in Saint Mary's Elementary & Junior High School and high school education in William R. Tolbert High School, St. Theresa's Convent and the American Cooperative School. She graduated in nursing inn the [[United States of America]], from nursing at [[Loma Linda University]]. She received her doctorate from the [[World Harvest Theological Seminary]] on Bible studies.<ref name=prof>{{cite web|title=Presidenial Candidate 2014|url=http://www.smolec.pl/kobiety/margaret_tor_thompson.htm|accessdate=23 October 2014|publisher=Smolec.pl}}</ref> Tor-Thomspson was a registered nurse, Christian educator and author. She served as the Chief Executive Office (CEO) for Non-governmental organisations like Women of Might among Nations (WOMAN) and also Voice of Liberia.<ref>[[#Human|Human Rights First 2005]] p. 7</ref> She was married to Dr. Charles Thompson and they have four daughters and two sons.<ref name=prof/>
==Political career== Tor-Thomson was the [[Freedom Alliance Party of Liberia]] (FAPL) presidential candidate in the [[Liberian general election, 2005|October 2005 elections]]. Her political manifesto in her own words was "I would make sure that the responsible people are prosecuted; that people understand the consequences; send out a clear-cut message that we will no longer tolerate crime with impunity".<ref>[[#Human|Human Rights First 2005]] p. 17</ref> She was one of the three female presidential candidates in the election. She secured 8,418 out of total 1,012,673 votes to secure 0.9 per cent of the mandate and securing 13th position.<ref>{{cite web|title=2005 Election Results, President and Vice-President Election|url=http://www.necliberia.org/results/President/President_ByVotes.php|publisher=National Elections Commission, Republic of Liberia|date=20 October 2005|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref> The elections saw a set of candidates like Alfred Reeves and George Kiadii along with her campaigning on fundamentalist Christian platform and were less successful.<ref>{{cite book|title=Civil War and State Formation: The Political Economy of War and Peace in Liberia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-OlQBXPc25oC&pg=PA195&dq=Margaret+Tor-Thompson&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjOuoiavfDPAhUP8WMKHc7aDIQQ6AEIGzAA#v=onepage&q=Margaret%20Tor-Thompson&f=false|page=195|first=Felix |last=Gerdes}}</ref> Her party could not win any seat in the Senate or House of representatives.<ref>{{cite news|title=GNN Begins Nationwide Opinion Poll For Liberia’s Pending Presidential election In 2017|url=http://gnnliberia.com/2015/08/30/gnn-begins-nationwide-opinion-poll-for-liberias-pending-presidential-election-in-2017/|date=30 August 2015|accessdate=23 October 2016|publisher=GNN Liberia}}</ref>
In late April 2007, it was reported that she died of [[breast cancer]] – the death certificate confirmed the cause and indicated that she died at [[Bushrod Island]] on 4 April 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Liberia: Margaret Thompson Died of Breast Cancer|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200705290464.html|publisher=The Inquirer|accessdate=23 October 2016|date=28 May 2007|isbn=9783593398921}}</ref>
