A '''shipping container clinic''' is a type of [[shipping container architecture]] using [[intermodal container]]s (shipping containers) as the structural element of a medical clinic that can be easily deployed to remote regions of the world. Shipping containers are ideal because of their inherent strength, wide availability and relatively low cost. In addition, and most relevant, shipping containers can be deployed anywhere in the world with the clinic already assembled within the container. This means pop-up clinics can be operational within days after deployment.
==History== Several organizations have developed the concept of shipping container clinics: * In 2005, Hospitals of Hope produced a "Clinic In A Can" in a 45-foot trailer that was sent to [[Les Cayes]], [[Haiti]] to provide medical relief.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hospitalsofhope.org/images/stories/Documents/news/aapa7-30-05.pdf|title=International Humanitarian of the Year|publisher=Hospitalsofhope.org|format=PDF|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> The 45 foot trailer is converted into five medical rooms, with each one being approximately 70 square feet. The container has since helped Hospitals of Hope provide care to over 30,000 residents of Haiti. * In 2006, [[Pulitzer Prize]] winning author, [[Laurie Garrett]], worked with Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute to create a prototype "Doc In A Box" based on Garrett's conceptual framework.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfr.org/projects/world/doc-in-a-box-project/pr1247|title=Doc-in-a-Box Project|work=Council on Foreign Relations|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lauriegarrett.com/index.php/en/progress/2542/ |accessdate=September 1, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004170956/http://www.lauriegarrett.com/index.php/en/progress/2542/ |archivedate=October 4, 2011 }}</ref> * In June 2010, Hospitals of Hope sent two "Clinic In A Cans" to Haiti in partnership with Heart to Heart International in response to the earthquake.<ref>{{cite news|first1 = Deb|last1 = Gruver |title = Hospitals for Hope converts shipping containers into clinics|url = http://www.kansas.com/news/local/article1021575.html|date = 26 January 2010|newspaper = The Wichita Eagle |accessdate = 2014-10-13}}</ref> The containers were both 40 foot long and cost around $12,000 to build. * In November 2010, Containers 2 Clinics sent a prototype clinic to be used on site at Grace Children's Hospital in [[Port-au-Prince]], [[Haiti]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://containers2clinics.org/documents/AC-MSH-C2C-GCH%20PR%20Nov%201.pdf|title=The Power of Partnership: Working Together to Restore Maternal and Pediatric Health in Haiti |publisher=Containers2clinics.org|format=PDF|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://containers2clinics.org/|title=Care 2 Communities|work=Care 2 Communities|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> * In April 2011, a three-unit Clinic In A Can was shipped to Haiti in partnership with Aslan Youth Ministries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clinicinacan.org/container-hospital-headed-for-haiti/|title=Container Clinic Headed for Haiti!|work=Clinic In A Can|accessdate=13 October 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141018082032/http://www.clinicinacan.org/container-hospital-headed-for-haiti/|archivedate=18 October 2014|df=}}</ref> This small hospital will be operated by Aslan Youth Ministries, an organization working in the north-east of Haiti. With a fault line running right under where they work, steel shipping containers are much safer than a concrete structure. * In August 2012, Clinics4All established its Global Clinic Donation Program (GCDP) to provide MEDICAL CLINICS free of charge to third-world Governments through their respective departments or Ministries of Health – as a means of assisting developing country Governments in improving access to healthcare in medically under-served and remote areas, particularly for children and women.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160304070031/http://www.clinics4all.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=43&Itemid=186] </ref> * In March 2013, Clinic In A Can shipped a solar powered clinic to [[Mirebalais]], [[Haiti]] in partnernship with Global Vision Citadelle Ministries, as well as a radiology Clinic In A Can to [[Freetown]], [[Sierra Leone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kansas.com/2013/03/12/2712596/local-nonprofit-to-send-2-clinic.html|title=Local nonprofit to send 2 ‘Clinic in a Can’ facilities overseas|work=kansas|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/wichita/news/2013/03/12/wichita-nonprofit-shipping-two.html|title=Wichita nonprofit shipping two portable medical clinics overseas|date=12 March 2013|work=Wichita Business Journal|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> * In July 2013, Arkitainer opened its doors as a UK based company specialising in the use of shipping containers for various community based projects. A recent proposal for a residential community complete with clinics, schooling and vocational training for Cape Town is currently underway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arkitainer.com|title=Arkitainer - Shipping Container Architecture - Arkitainer - Shipping Container Architecture|publisher=Arkitainer.com|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref>
